# Example ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_* configuration for pointing the generic HTTP
# target provider (packages/core/src/providers/http-target.ts) at an
# APEX-OmniHub agent endpoint.
#
# This file is a REFERENCE EXAMPLE ONLY — it is not read by Armageddon Core
# automatically, is not APEX-OmniHub-specific code, and nothing in
# packages/core/src special-cases APEX-OmniHub. Copy the values you need into
# your own .env.moat or export them before running `armageddon run`.
#
# Background (from a live discovery pass over the APEX-OmniHub repo,
# UNVERIFIED beyond static code reading — confirm against the actual
# deployment before use):
#
#   - supabase/functions/apex-agent/index.ts is a simple, synchronous
#     request/response endpoint: POST {query, traceId} -> raw orchestrator
#     JSON response (shape depends on the operator's ORCHESTRATOR_URL, so
#     ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_RESPONSE_PATH below may need adjusting per deployment).
#     Auth is a real Supabase user JWT. This is the easier fit for this
#     provider today because it's a plain JSON call, not a stream.
#
#   - functions/api/mcp/invoke.ts ("OmniPort Gateway", served at
#     /api/mcp/invoke) is the more contract-consistent, better-tested real
#     agent surface, but responds over Server-Sent Events
#     (status/completed/failed/timeout frames), which this v1 HTTP provider
#     does NOT parse — it expects a single JSON response body. Pointing this
#     provider at it as-is will very likely fail to extract a usable reply.
#     Wiring SSE support is a reasonable follow-up if you want to target this
#     endpoint instead.
#
#   - supabase/functions/byom-proxy is a direct pass-through to real
#     Anthropic/Groq provider keys and spends real money per call — only
#     point Armageddon at it with a dedicated sandbox tenant and a
#     capped/test provider key, never a shared production key.
#
# Use a dedicated staging/sandbox test-user bearer token for
# ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_AUTH_HEADER_ENV's underlying value. Do not use a
# production personal account token, and do not use the Supabase service
# role key unless you are deliberately testing a backend eval harness that
# is designed for service-role execution.

ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_PROVIDER=http
ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_ENDPOINT=https://<supabase-project>.supabase.co/functions/v1/apex-agent
ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_METHOD=POST
ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_BODY_TEMPLATE={"query":"{{prompt}}","traceId":"{{uuid}}"}
# Adjust to match whatever your ORCHESTRATOR_URL actually returns.
ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_RESPONSE_PATH=data.reply
ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_AUTH_HEADER_ENV=APEX_OMNIHUB_TEST_BEARER
# Default-deny: the endpoint's host MUST appear here verbatim.
ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_ALLOWLIST_HOSTS=<supabase-project>.supabase.co
ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_TIMEOUT_MS=30000
ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_MAX_RPM=10

# Set the actual staging/sandbox bearer token in the env var named above,
# e.g.:
#   export APEX_OMNIHUB_TEST_BEARER="<staging test-user JWT>"
#
# A Supabase project host is not a staging/sandbox/dev hostname by itself —
# if it doesn't otherwise look non-production, buildHttpTargetConfig() will
# refuse to run without also setting:
#   ARMAGEDDON_TARGET_ALLOW_PRODUCTION_HOST=true
# Only set that if you have deliberately decided this project ref is a
# staging/sandbox project and not the production one.
